### 1. One-Line Summary
* G-1: Higher ceiling for heavy topspin with a firmer, more direct bite; excels when you can engage the sponge cleanly.
* Vega Pro: More forgiving “classic ESN” all-rounder with easy access to spin and control; slightly lower top-end but smoother to use.

### 2. Head-to-Head Breakdown
* **Speed & Gears:**
    * **Low Impact:**
        * G-1: Medium bounce; needs a bit more intent to “wake up,” especially on soft touches.
        * Vega Pro: Easier rebound and pace with compact strokes; feels more lively at low effort.
    * **Top End:**
        * G-1: Higher top-end when you fully engage; stronger through the ball from mid-distance.
        * Vega Pro: Solid but tops out earlier; relies more on timing than sheer power on big swings.
    * **Linearity:**
        * G-1: More linear and predictable once engaged; rewards clean contact and good acceleration.
        * Vega Pro: Slightly more “springy” feel; can jump a bit when you cross the sponge engagement threshold.

* **Spin Mechanics:**
    * **Opening Loop:**
        * G-1: Very strong on the first loop vs backspin if you brush with commitment; heavy, biting arc.
        * Vega Pro: Easier to open with a shorter motion; high consistency even if contact is a bit thin.
    * **Max Spin:**
        * G-1: Higher peak spin and heavier ball on full strokes; excellent for pressure topspin patterns.
        * Vega Pro: High spin for its class, but less “loaded” at maximum compared to G-1.
    * **Topsheet Grip:**
        * G-1: Grippy and firm; bites well on brush contact and holds stability under hard impact.
        * Vega Pro: Very grippy but feels softer; excels at “grab and lift” with medium power.

* **Flight Path (Throw Angle):**
    * **Arc Height:**
        * G-1: Medium-high throw with a more penetrating arc when you drive forward.
        * Vega Pro: Medium-high to high throw; naturally clears the net with safer arc.
    * **Safety:**
        * G-1: High safety when your timing is good; punishes lazy contact more.
        * Vega Pro: Higher “built-in” safety on imperfect contact; easier depth control in rallies.

* **Feel & Feedback:**
    * **Sensation:**
        * G-1: Firmer, crisper, more direct; clear feedback on contact quality.
        * Vega Pro: Slightly softer and more cushioned; smoother feel with less sharp feedback.
    * **Dwell:**
        * G-1: Medium dwell; grips well but releases decisively when you accelerate.
        * Vega Pro: Medium-long dwell; holds the ball a touch longer, aiding spin and control.

* **Control & Short Game:**
    * **Sensitivity:**
        * G-1: More sensitive to incoming spin at higher impact; demands cleaner angles on receive.
        * Vega Pro: A bit less punishing; easier to manage serve/receive with compact technique.
    * **Touch Play:**
        * G-1: Very stable for pushes and short stops once you adjust; lower “auto-bounce.”
        * Vega Pro: Easier drop shots and flips; can pop up if your hand is too passive.

* **Blocking & Countering:**
    * **Passive Block:**
        * G-1: Stable but firmer; requires good bat angle—less automatic on high-spin topspin.
        * Vega Pro: More forgiving; absorbs and redirects well with simple positioning.
    * **Active Counter:**
        * G-1: Excellent for punchy counters and re-loops; strong bite and forward drive.
        * Vega Pro: Very good for close-table counter topspin; slightly less “finish” power.

### 3. The Recommendation
* **Choose G-1 if:**
    * You value maximum spin and a heavier ball on full swings.
    * You prefer a firmer, more direct feel with clearer feedback.
    * You play aggressive topspin patterns (serve + 3rd ball, counter-looping) and can engage the sponge reliably.
    * You’re comfortable managing higher sensitivity on receive and faster exchanges.

* **Choose Vega Pro if:**
    * You want an easier, more forgiving rubber that still has strong spin.
    * You prioritize consistency in opening loops, blocks, and all-round rally control.
    * You like a slightly softer, more cushioned feel for touch play and close-table exchanges.
    * You want a reliable “do-everything” ESN rubber with great value and fewer sharp demands.